Date: Fri 29 Mar 2002
From: D.A.Henderson, M.D.,M.P.H. <Dahzero@aol.com>

Comment from Dr. Henderson on the Status of the Aventis Smallpox
Vaccine
------------------------------------------------------------------------
The vaccine that has recently surfaced [see: Smallpox, diluted vaccine
trial (08) 20020329.3841 was produced in Swiftwater, Pennsylvania,
somewhat more than 40 years ago. The virus titers are generally at 7.5
logs or better, i.e. above the international standard of that time. This
reinforces the belief that [smallpox vaccine, properly preserved,
retains its potency for many, many decades.
The vaccine dilution trials only serve to confirm studies that were done
nearly 50 years ago and repeated on several occasions. Thus, even
these long preserved vaccines perform exactly as you might expect
provided that proper vaccination technique is employed.
Bifurcated needles are essential. The ordinary hypodermic needle or the
lancet will not get these results with the same small amount of vaccine.
There is one manufacturer, Precision, that is now making large
numbers of bifurcated needles but there are at least two other
commercial manufacturers that are commencing production.
--
D.A.Henderson, M.D.,M.P.H.
Director, Office of Public Health Preparedness
Department of Health and Human Services
200 Independence Avenue, SW
Room 636 G
Washington, D.C. 20201
